videoTitle: Working a Construction Job
commentText: Im one of the few that got out.  Took the job offer from my uncle when i was 17, worked there for a year and a half while going to night school, loved it at first.  The only issue is working with my uncle sucks, hes the type to put others down to make himself look good and can never be wrong.  It was the same with one of the old guys there, the young generations is so weak willed and never wants to do shit, all i had to hear everyday at lunch.  Started eating in my truck every day, talking a lot less, just putting earbuds and going to work, i liked the hanging with the other guys my age, we were all in the same boat somewhat but they were a couple years older so they werent completely relateable.  It got to the point of me dreading waking up and going to work, not because of hard it was, the 11 hour shift and then going to school for 3 or 4 hours, it wasnt the shoveling gravels for 9 hours straight at 103F outside, it was the fact i had to get up and deal with those assholes for hours.  I finally finished night school and put in my 2 weeks to get ready for college to get my bachelors to become a therapist, it was the great 2 months of my life being free from everything for once.  My college plan has since fell through since i had to leave to take care of my mom but im a lot happier than i was then.

Anyone going into a career should do it out of wanting to be there, not just because they need to optimize the paycheck and which government programs will reduce their long term debt.

Even for graduates entering through the direct entry route, the minimum duration is 4.5 years. commentText: Retired LEO, 25 years. I left in disgust with my department and the profession as a whole. I've read a lot of comments about senior command staff being the biggest problem. I totally agree. The world thinks so much of police, but they have no idea what it is really like. They have no idea what people will do to each other to get promoted,  to get that special detail, to get that detective position. People would always say to me, "you guys don't get paid enough..." You are correct. But not for the reasons you think. I carried a gun, wore body armor and was trained to deal with all sorts of threats from domestic encounters, three hundred pound drunks, meth heads and active shooters. But there is no armor, no training that can protect you from a weaponized administration. The world would be shocked at the things I have seen.  But now I have a nice job and get a check every month from my department's retirement that reminds me that I don't have those problems any more.   All the best, young lady.  You got out alive.

commentText: I'm 57. I got hit with a lay off after nine years.  I did the on line crap and got no where.  I drove to a temp service and instantly got an interview the next day and got hired on the spot.  The place is less than seven miles from my house.  If you're serious about getting a job then look for a temp service close to you and physically go to it.  Companies go to them for people to hire as temps so they can simply call them if you don't end up working out.  You work as a temp for a while and if you prove yourself you get hired after a period of time.  I was only out of work for like a week and a half.  I make five bucks less per hour but I did finish paying off my truck so no car payment helps.

commentText: Today layoffs have nothing to do with AI. Sure LLMs (and the following models) are going to involves layoffs, but in the 10 next years. The number of organisations who are *already* able to replace humans with AI is very very small. Today layoffs are more about a global crisis, with inflation, a US president disturbing the world economy, the invasion of Ukraine, climate warming (just the beginning...), etc. So sure, AI will take jobs, as robots did in factories decades ago, but it just means more time for other activities, at least with the proper political regime (not all for the already most wealthy).

commentText: I want to make one correction to the lady around 9:17. The word you're looking for is "automated tracking system" or ATS. Examples include Workday and Talio. These are not new and as a 32 year old when I graduated when I was younger I encountered them as well (circa 2015-2016). ATS systems have nothing to do with the impact ChatGPT and generative AI has on the labour market and it's not helpful to confuse the two. People have been complaining about ATS systems for a very long time, even before ChatGPT and the like existed. The time when humans would review applications was a very long time ago, like maybe 2010 or thereabouts.

In my view, we are seeing a split in the dev market: 'Orchestration' (translating specs to code) is now an AI commodity. commentText: AI isn't taking jobs, it's AI speculation that's taking jobs. AI has generally underperformed everywhere it's been implemented, with studies generally showing it makes workers less efficient (which the media should know, considering the high-profile embarrassments they've had). As the for the hype, it's largely driven by a mix of speculation, advertising/marketing, and bad assumptions about generative AI's current capabilities. All that said, the reporter(s) and pundit(s) for this story could easily lose their jobs to AI without anything of value being lost because their claims involve as much hallucination and shoddy information as AI.

commentText: Ex-truck driver here.   I drove Cents Per Mile, owner operator and lease operator. OTR.   It not very profitable.   -owner operator. If you buy a brand new truck, your expenses go towards the truck payment, trailer payment (which is another expense), insurance for both truck and trailer, insurance for the loads, fuel for both truck and trailer, IFTA,  Tolls (east coast tolls are absurdly expensive) . Plus,  repair schedules. Also, depends highly on what the market offers and other factors. Sure, you can earn 350k - 450k gross per year. BUT, with all of those expenses  you will net under 60k per year. And then you're taxed on personal income.  If you buy USED equipment, the same as above applies, except now there are major pending issues, repairs, and preventive  maintenance. Your equipment will become a risk factor. -Cpm (cent per mile) you can earn 50-75 cents per mile, but most  if not all, companies have you running from zipcode to zipcode basis instead of per mile. You have no control on maintenance and no control on basically anything. And then escrow gets removed, also, personal tax at 33%.  -lease operator is almost a hybrid of both owner and CPM, just depending of the clauses being signed for at the beginning of your contract agreements.  The only and best way to make good money is if you own a company and have everyone else work for you,  take no executive decisions with 200+ trucks, have your own shop, have your own insurance firm and have PRISTINE, loyal and fully dedicated drivers under your belt. But, that is just a dream.

For most local jobs though I would say expect to make around 60-80k and if hauling hazmat maybe up to 100k or decently more depending on area. Still better than a lot and more than enough to live on depending on your area.  You could also work for a mega carrier (Big Fleet companies like Swift, CR England, knight, etc.) and eventually become a trainer. commentText: Call centre really isn't so bad at all. I did it for about 7 months this year to bridge a gap, and it was pretty chill. videoDescription: The tech job market right now is brutal. Layoffs, endless applications, and constant rejections. It feels impossible to land an offer.
commentText: I've come to the conclusion that I no longer want to chase after a language or framework. This changes all the time. I've also decided that I will no longer subject myself to being treated like a commodity at a cattle auction. In the end, all of this is designed to make you accept doing more for less. I think at some point we give in and accept unrealistic things because the "market demands it," or the influencer you follow or the group of followers in the bubble you're in dictates that this is the culture, technology, or method to be adopted. Yes, I went through a financial setback and had to accept working in other segments. But that didn't kill my desire to work with software. Today, I think the path is to work as an entrepreneur and consultant for small businesses, creating solutions for the region you live in or where you can work without creating a burden on your life. Another mistake I see is the industrialization of the IT workforce. We didn't start that way; we started in a garage or on a small project; we're not cattle.

commentText: I worked in tech for 45 years in several roles. When I started, ‚ÄúBeing in computers.‚Äù, was like saying you were a Wizard in a tower. Your job was mysterious and magical and few others were in the industry competing for these enchanted positions. I retired a few years ago. commentText: Imagine if medical schools trained all doctors to be general practitioners.  And they had to figure it out for themselves, how to become a cardiologist, or an oncologist, etc.  That's kinda what it's like being an entry level software developer.  There is a big jump in your marketability once you have 2 - 4 years of experience.  But primarily in the application/industry of your current job.  It's very common for people to leave SW dev fairly early in their career.  The industry-specific stuff they needed to learn to develop the code ends up being more valuable than their SW dev skills.  Software doesn't wear out.  New software has to be better than old software, to somebody, if it's going to make sense to pay SW devs to make it.  People tolerate older stuff more, when they are hoarding cash in anticipation of bad times.  It's just been a while since there's been so much anticipation of bad times ahead.  The Big Bill restored some tax advantages for R&D spending I think, which hopefully will help these recent grades.  Programmer productivity has steeply and steadily increased over the years, due to improvements in programming languages and other tools.  It's often good for productivity (if not quality) to alter existing code for new purposes, rather than start from scratch.  Open source practices enable companies to repurpose each other's code, not just their own.  I don't think AI LLMs could have been trained to code without open source.  Remains to be seen what the impact will be.  If there is a net SW dev job loss, it will be the lower paid ones lost.  The biggest impact in tech will probably be chatbots doing first tier tech support.  My perspective as a SW dev who retired early after being laid off in 2024.

commentText: The last decade? Honestly, I do feel empathy for the people who got in too late. In fact, I have mentored several over the past few years, one of them just getting a job in a very tight market. I know it is a struggle, but I am 65, retiring this year as a software engineer. My father worked in computers in the 50's when programs ran on tape drives and punch cards, initially for the military and then later for IBM and Honeywell. His brother saw the chance and started working with computers for major corporations like AmEx and Shearson-Lehman. In the 70s and 80s my aunts would say to me, "Go into computers, it's the wave of the future." It has been a long run. BTW, this was never my intent. Although I did half a degree in CS, I really wanted to go into medicine and management. That was always my interest, but at some point, my enjoyment of coding and the availability of high-paying work, made it my career.

commentText: You may get bites from very small firms. For larger firms, this is worse than contacting recruiter directly. Interviewing screening and such are usually side things for hiring managers and are more focused on their primary senior job duties. They will more than likely get annoyed and ignore it completely. Especially these days where applicant to role ratios are wack. Chances are they already have dozens of folks contacting them directly.  Networking helps a lot: job fairs, friends, family, hobby groups. Have multiple people look over your resume. Practice interviewing. Other than that it's a number game.

videoTitle: What the Unemployment Rate Isn't Telling Us
videoDescription: The latest job report shows that the unemployment rate remains steady, but it's not telling the full story. Lydia DePillis, an economy ...
commentText: As someone who has been downsized more than once, I always hate hearing that unemployment numbers are the people who are looking for work or that unemployment numbers are down in part because some people stopped looking for work, which is a misnomer. Those numbers indicate people who are enrolled in unemployment insurance benefits. There are many unemployed people who are not on unemployment insurance benefits for a variety of reasons. Their benefits may have run out before they could obtain employment. They might be unemployed and busy as a caregiver for one or more family members, unpaid and not enrolled in unemployment insurance benefits. They go uncounted.
